 {"id":"asupersync-4l9iw.1","title":"[WASM][Rust API] Define the supported Rust-authored Browser Edition API surface","description":"Define exactly what it means to write Browser Edition code directly in Rust and compile it to wasm. The current docs say the semantic core is portable but the Rust-authored wasm path is not yet documented, tested, or public, which leaves a gap between architectural possibility and actual product support.\n\nThis task establishes the supported Rust authoring model, the intended crate and feature surface, and the boundaries that remain browser-only or intentionally unsupported.","design":"Specify a truthful Rust-authored browser contract before adding examples or public claims. The design should state which runtime concepts, capabilities, and feature gates are intended to be public for browser-targeted Rust code, and which native-only surfaces remain outside the Rust-to-wasm story.\n\nThis should align with the same support matrix used for JS and TS consumers so the project does not accidentally create one product story for JavaScript and a different, fuzzier one for Rust.","acceptance_criteria":"1. There is a precise supported Rust-authored browser API model with explicit scope and non-goals.\n2. The defined surface aligns with the browser support matrix rather than implying extra native parity.\n3. Future implementation tasks can proceed without reopening design ambiguity about what Rust consumers are promised.","notes":"This task is foundational because public API ambiguity is how wasm support drifts into folklore. The Browser Edition needs a single honest Rust consumer story.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:29:15.346565774Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-15T20:01:53.455457259Z","closed_at":"2026-03-15T20:01:53.455428276Z","close_reason":"Defined the Rust-authored Browser Edition contract in README.md, docs/WASM.md, and docs/wasm_quickstart_migration.md","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["browser","rust-api","vnext","wasm"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.1","depends_on_id":"asupersync-4l9iw","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:29:15.346565774Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-4l9iw.2","title":"[WASM][Rust API] Ship a canonical Rust-authored browser example and package layout","description":"Build the canonical example that proves the Rust-authored browser path is real. This should show how a Rust consumer writes Browser Edition logic, compiles to wasm, bootstraps in a supported browser context, and interacts with explicit browser-safe capabilities.\n\nThe example and package layout should be maintained artifacts, not one-off experiments or hidden integration tests.","design":"Use the supported API model from the previous task to create a canonical example that future maintainers can run, inspect, and extend. The package layout should clarify where Rust-authored browser code belongs, how it is built, and how browser bootstrapping differs from native runtime setup.\n\nThe example should demonstrate explicit capability usage rather than relying on magical globals or undocumented glue.","acceptance_criteria":"1. A maintained example shows a supported Rust-authored browser workflow from source to running browser artifact.\n2. The packaging and build layout are documented enough that new Rust consumers can follow them without reading internal code first.\n3. The example stays within the declared browser support matrix and does not imply native-only features are available.","notes":"If the Rust path has no canonical example, it is not actually public. Examples are part of the contract, not decorative extras.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"RainyBadger","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:29:35.796897311Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-15T20:28:27.460688134Z","closed_at":"2026-03-15T20:28:27.460662657Z","close_reason":"Completed: maintained Rust-browser consumer fixture + validator + contract coverage","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["browser","example","rust-api","vnext","wasm"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.2","depends_on_id":"asupersync-4l9iw","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:29:35.796897311Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.2","depends_on_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:29:52.982502587Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-4l9iw.3","title":"[WASM][Rust API] Add wasm-browser harness coverage for Rust-authored scopes, cancellation, and capabilities","description":"Validate the Rust-authored browser path with real coverage rather than with example-only confidence. This task adds harness tests that exercise Rust-authored scopes, task lifecycle, cancellation, and browser-safe capability use against supported wasm browser targets.\n\nIts role is to prove that the Rust path preserves the same core invariants as the JS and TS consumer path within the browser execution model.","design":"Exercise the Rust-authored browser path at the semantic level that matters: scopes, child work, cancellation, shutdown, and browser-safe capability access. The harness should show that Rust-authored browser code preserves structured-concurrency rules instead of only compiling successfully.\n\nCoverage should align with the supported API model and canonical example rather than testing undefined or not-yet-public surfaces.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Automated browser-targeted coverage exists for Rust-authored scopes, lifecycle behavior, cancellation, and browser-safe capability use.\n2. The tests validate invariants that matter to Asupersync rather than only smoke-testing compilation.\n3. Coverage stays aligned with the declared public Rust-authored browser API surface.","notes":"A compile-only story would be misleading here. This task exists so maintainers can prove that Rust-authored browser code behaves correctly, not merely that it links.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"FrostyForge","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:30:03.534252714Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-16T03:25:54.554288613Z","closed_at":"2026-03-16T03:25:53.624543929Z","close_reason":"Strengthened real-browser Rust WASM harness assertions for lifecycle, cancellation, event coverage, and browser capabilities","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["browser","rust-api","testing","vnext","wasm"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.3","depends_on_id":"asupersync-4l9iw","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:30:03.534252714Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.3","depends_on_id":"asupersync-4l9iw.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:30:43.446928753Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-4l9iw.4","title":"[WASM][Rust API] Publish migration and usage guidance for Rust-authored browser consumers","description":"Turn the Rust-authored browser path into documented product guidance. This task writes the migration and usage material that explains who should use the Rust-authored path, how it differs from the JS or TS package path, which browser contexts are supported, and where native-only expectations must stop.\n\nIt exists so future users and maintainers do not have to infer the Rust browser story from scattered examples and comments.","design":"Write migration and usage guidance from the perspective of a real Rust consumer, not from internal architectural shorthand. The material should explain the supported build path, runtime assumptions, capability model, and unsupported browser or native surfaces in a way that stays aligned with the example and test harness.\n\nKeep the messaging consistent with the boundary epic so Rust consumers do not receive a looser or more optimistic story than JS and TS consumers.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Maintained documentation explains when and how to use the Rust-authored browser path.\n2. The guidance distinguishes supported browser contexts, guarded optional surfaces, bridge-only scenarios, and native-only non-goals.\n3. The docs remain aligned with the canonical example and harness coverage rather than promising more than the code proves.","notes":"This is the final contract-closure step for the Rust browser lane. Without it, the project still effectively treats the path as a private capability.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"LilacPrairie","created_at":"2026-03-15T06:31:01.155703161Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-16T03:54:12.058456287Z","closed_at":"2026-03-16T03:54:12.058427293Z","close_reason":"Published truthful Rust-authored browser guidance aligned to live wasm profile gates, fixture workflow, and integration entrypoints","source_repo":".","comp